<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="33" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,1322,2028]" pageId="6" pageNumber="33">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,326,1602,1628]" pageId="6" pageNumber="33">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Palest and one of the largest species. 
<taxonomicName box="[769,923,1603,1628]" class="Insecta" family="Corduliidae" genus="Hemicordulia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="6" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="atrovirens">
<emphasis box="[769,923,1603,1628]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="33">H. atrovirens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from neighbouring 
<collectingCountry box="[1158,1260,1602,1628]" name="Réunion" pageId="6" pageNumber="33">Réunion</collectingCountry>
, by contrast, is the darkest known. The two species agree in their large size, high Ax and Px counts, thick blunt-tipped cerci (
<figureCitation box="[159,263,1682,1708]" captionStart="FIGURES 2 – 11. 2 – 6" captionStartId="5.[151,269,1923,1947]" captionTargetBox="[264,1285,480,1866]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[264,1323,469,1891]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 2 – 11. 2 – 6, Male appendages of Hemicordulia species in dorsal view. (2) H. asiatica; (3) H. virens; (4) H. atrovirens n. sp.; (5) H. similis; (6) H. africana n. sp.; 7 – 11, Male appendages of Hemicordulia species in lateral view. (7) H. asiatica; (8) H. virens; (9) H. atrovirens n. sp.; (10) H. similis; (11) H. africana n. sp." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/175931/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="33">
Figs 
<number box="[218,263,1682,1708]" pageId="6" pageNumber="33" value="3.8">3, 8</number>
</figureCitation>
) and the basal position of the vulvar scale (
<figureCitation box="[773,860,1682,1708]" captionStart="FIGURES 12 – 17" captionStartId="7.[151,269,1642,1666]" captionTargetBox="[265,1323,403,1602]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[263,1323,356,1636]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 12 – 17. Vulvar scale and S 9 of Hemicordulia species in ventral view. (12) H. asiatica; (13) H. virens; (14) H. atrovirens n. sp.; (15) aberrant H. similis (cf. Fraser 1949); (16) typical H. similis; (17) H. africana n. sp." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/175932/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="33">
Fig. 
<number box="[828,860,1682,1708]" pageId="6" pageNumber="33" value="13.0">13</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
